      "title": "Method validation: based on error analysis",
      "instruction": "In the following theorem, the truncation error of the Taylor expansion for the exact solution of Eq. (1) is used to evaluate the error bound for the approximate solution fňúN(z).Theorem 1LetfňúN(z)be the approximate solution andf(z)be the exact solutions ofEq. (1). Iff(z)has(N+1)times continuous derivative, then the error bound for the absolute error is given by|f(z)‚ąífňúN(z)|‚Č§|RNT(z)|+|fNT(z)‚ąífňúN(z)|.WherefNT(z)denotes theNthdegree Taylor polynomial off(z)around the pointz=z0‚ąąDandRNT(z)represents its Cauchy form remainder term[46].ProofThe Taylor series can be rewritten with reminder term of f(z) around the point z0‚ąąD asf(z)=‚ąĎj=0N(z‚ąíz0)jj!f(j)(z0)+RNT(z).WhereRNT(z)=12ŌÄi‚ąģő≥(z‚ąíz0t‚ąíz0)(N+1)f(t)t‚ąízdt is the Cauchy form reminder term of the Taylor expansion of f(z) and this contour integral is evaluated around the circle ő≥ which centered at z0, such that ő≥‚äāD\n[19]. Consequently, RNT(z)=f(z)‚ąífNT(z). By using this in conjunction with the triangle inequality, we get|f(z)‚ąífňúN(z)|=|f(z)‚ąífňúN(z)+fNT(z)‚ąífNT(z)|‚Č§|f(z)‚ąífNT(z)|+|fNT(z)‚ąífňúN(z)|=|RNT(z)|+|fNT(z)‚ąífňúN(x)|.As a result, we have located an upper bound for the absolute error based on the Taylor truncation error of the exact solution.¬†‚Ė°",
